    { id: 'faq',         label: 'FAQ' },
  ]}
  relatedLinks={[
    { href: '/adjustment-of-status',         label: 'AOS Complete Guide' },
    { href: '/adjustment-of-status-after-marriage', label: 'AOS After K-1 Marriage' },
    { href: '/conditional-green-card',       label: 'Conditional Green Card' },
    { href: '/i-751-petition-remove-conditions', label: 'Remove Conditions (I-751)' },
    { href: '/k1-visa-cost',                 label: 'K-1 Visa Total Cost' },
    { href: '/green-card-through-marriage',  label: 'Green Card Through Marriage' },
  ]}
>

<h2 id="overview">AOS Timeline Overview</h2>
<p><SmartLink href="/adjustment-of-status">Adjustment of Status (AOS)</SmartLink> is the process of obtaining a U.S. green card from inside the United States — used by <SmartLink href="/k1-visa">K-1 visa</SmartLink> holders after marriage, and by anyone on a valid nonimmigrant status who married a U.S. citizen. The core form is <strong><SmartLink href="/i-485">I-485 (Application to Register Permanent Residence)</SmartLink></strong>.</p>
<p>Total AOS processing in 2026 takes <strong>12–24 months</strong> from the date USCIS receives your package to green card approval. The exact time depends heavily on which USCIS field office handles your case — some offices run significantly faster or slower than average.</p>

<div class="art-info">
  <strong>K-1 holders: file AOS within 90 days of entry</strong>
  <p>If you entered on a K-1 fiancé visa, you must marry your petitioner within 90 days and file for AOS promptly. There's no strict deadline after marriage, but your K-1 status expires 90 days after entry — filing AOS is what maintains your lawful presence. Full walkthrough: <SmartLink href="/adjustment-of-status-after-marriage">AOS after K-1 marriage →</SmartLink></p>
</div>

<h2 id="by-stage">Stage-by-Stage Breakdown</h2>

<table class="art-table">
  <thead><tr><th>Stage</th><th>Timeline</th><th>What Happens</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>USCIS receives package</td><td>Day 1</td><td>I-485 + I-765 + I-131 + I-693 + fee payment accepted</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Receipt notices mailed</td><td>2–4 weeks</td><td>One receipt per form — save these, they have your case numbers</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Biometrics appointment</td><td>4–8 weeks</td><td>Fingerprints + photo at Application Support Center (ASC)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>EAD / Advance Parole issued</td><td>3–6 months</td><td>Combo card allows work + travel while I-485 pending</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Background checks complete</td><td>Ongoing</td><td>FBI name check, IBIS check — usually invisible to applicant</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Interview notice mailed</td><td>8–16 months</td><td>Local USCIS field office schedules your in-person interview</td></tr>
    <tr><td>AOS interview</td><td>10–18 months</td><td>Officer reviews relationship and eligibility; decision often same day</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Green card mailed</td><td>2–4 weeks post-interview</td><td>Conditional (2-year) or permanent (10-year) card sent by mail</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2 id="by-office">Processing Times by Field Office (2026)</h2>
<p>AOS processing times vary dramatically by USCIS field office. Officers at high-volume offices like Los Angeles and New York have heavier caseloads than smaller offices. The table below shows approximate current ranges — always verify at <a href="https://egov.uscis.gov/processing-times/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">egov.uscis.gov/processing-times</a>.</p>

<table class="art-table">
  <thead><tr><th>Field Office City</th><th>Approx. I-485 Processing Time</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Atlanta, GA</td><td>14–20 months</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Chicago, IL</td><td>16–22 months</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Dallas, TX</td><td>12–18 months</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Denver, CO</td><td>12–16 months</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Houston, TX</td><td>14–20 months</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Los Angeles, CA</td><td>18–24 months</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Miami, FL</td><td>14–20 months</td></tr>
    <tr><td>New York, NY</td><td>18–24 months</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Philadelphia, PA</td><td>14–18 months</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Phoenix, AZ</td><td>12–16 months</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Seattle, WA</td><td>14–20 months</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<div class="art-warn">
  <strong>These are estimates, not guarantees</strong>
  <p>USCIS processing times fluctuate with staffing, policy changes, and application volumes. Always check the official tool at <a href="https://egov.uscis.gov/processing-times/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">egov.uscis.gov/processing-times</a> for current data — published times are updated monthly.</p>
</div>

<h2 id="ead">EAD Work Permit & Advance Parole Timeline</h2>
<p>When you file I-485, you can file two additional forms concurrently at no extra fee:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Form I-765 (<SmartLink href="/employment-authorization">EAD</SmartLink>)</strong> — Employment Authorization Document; allows you to work legally in the U.S. while your green card is pending</li>
  <li><strong>Form I-131 (<SmartLink href="/advance-parole">Advance Parole</SmartLink>)</strong> — travel document allowing you to leave and re-enter the U.S. without abandoning your AOS</li>
</ul>
<p>USCIS typically issues a <strong>combo card</strong> that serves as both EAD and Advance Parole in one. Current processing time: <strong>3–6 months</strong>. USCIS has a 90-day processing target for initial EADs filed with I-485.</p>

<div class="art-info">
  <strong>Do NOT travel without Advance Parole</strong>
  <p>Leaving the U.S. while your I-485 is pending — without an approved Advance Parole — is generally considered an abandonment of your AOS application. Wait for your combo card before any international travel.</p>
</div>

<h2 id="delays">What Causes AOS Delays</h2>
<div class="art-tips">
  <div class="art-tip">
    <div class="art-tip-num">Cause 01</div>
    <div class="art-tip-title">Field office backlog</div>
    <div class="art-tip-desc">High-volume offices (LA, NYC) simply have more cases than lower-volume ones. You can't change which office handles your case — it's determined by your home address.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-tip">
    <div class="art-tip-num">Cause 02</div>
    <div class="art-tip-title">Request for Evidence (RFE)</div>
    <div class="art-tip-desc">USCIS sends an RFE if your package is missing documents or evidence is insufficient. Each RFE cycle pauses your case and typically adds 3–6 months.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-tip">
    <div class="art-tip-num">Cause 03</div>
    <div class="art-tip-title">Background check delays</div>
    <div class="art-tip-desc">FBI name checks and IBIS background screenings can take longer for common names or complex travel/employment histories. Typically invisible — you just wait.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-tip">
    <div class="art-tip-num">Cause 04</div>
    <div class="art-tip-title">Expired or incomplete I-693 medical exam</div>
    <div class="art-tip-desc">The I-693 medical exam must be performed by a USCIS-designated civil surgeon and sealed. If it expires before USCIS adjudicates, you'll need to redo it — adding months and cost.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-tip">
    <div class="art-tip-num">Cause 05</div>
    <div class="art-tip-title">Address change not reported</div>
    <div class="art-tip-desc">If you move and don't update USCIS (via AR-11 within 10 days of moving), notices go to the wrong address. This can cause a missed interview or RFE response deadline.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-tip">
    <div class="art-tip-num">Cause 06</div>
    <div class="art-tip-title">Complex or sensitive case factors</div>
    <div class="art-tip-desc">Prior immigration violations, criminal history (even minor), prior visa denials, or large age gaps may trigger additional review or a second interview, adding months.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<h2 id="check">How to Check Your AOS Case Status</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Online:</strong> <a href="https://my.uscis.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">my.uscis.gov</a> → Case Status — enter your I-485 receipt number (starts with IOE, EAC, WAC, or MSC)</li>
  <li><strong>Email/text alerts:</strong> Sign up for case status notifications at <a href="https://my.uscis.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">my.uscis.gov</a></li>
  <li><strong>USCIS Contact Center:</strong> 1-800-375-5283 — have your receipt number ready</li>
  <li><strong>Case inquiry:</strong> If your case is outside published processing times, submit an online inquiry through <a href="https://my.uscis.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">my.uscis.gov</a> — eligible after the published time has passed</li>
  <li><strong>InfoPass / in-person appointment:</strong> For urgent situations, you can request an in-person appointment at your local field office through the USCIS Contact Center</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="art-faq">
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">How long does Adjustment of Status take in 2026?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p>Most spousal AOS cases take <strong>12–24 months</strong> from filing to green card approval. High-volume offices like Los Angeles and New York run closer to 20–24 months; smaller offices can process in 12–16 months.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">How long does it take to get an EAD work permit during AOS?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p>Currently <strong>3–6 months</strong> when filed concurrently with I-485. USCIS has a 90-day processing goal for initial EADs. You'll receive a combo card (EAD + Advance Parole) in most cases.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">Can I travel outside the U.S. while AOS is pending?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p>Only with an approved Advance Parole document (Form I-131, typically issued as part of the combo card). Leaving without it is generally treated as abandonment of your I-485 application.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">What is the AOS interview and when does it happen?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p>An in-person interview at your local USCIS field office, typically <strong>10–18 months</strong> after filing. The officer reviews your relationship evidence and confirms your eligibility. Many cases are approved same day or within weeks of the interview.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">How do I check my AOS case status?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p>Log in to my.uscis.gov and enter your I-485 receipt number. You can also sign up for automatic case status alerts by email or text.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">What causes AOS delays?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p>The most common causes: field office backlog, RFEs for missing or insufficient documents, background check delays, expired I-693 medical exam, unreported address changes, and complex case factors like prior immigration issues.</p></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="art-cta-dark">
  <h2>Waiting on your AOS? Know your rights.</h2>
  <p>An immigration attorney can submit a case inquiry, respond to RFEs, and help you understand your options if your case is unusually delayed.</p>
  <a href="/adjustment-of-status" class="art-btn-white">Full AOS Guide →</a>
  <a href="#" class="art-btn-ghost" data-affiliate="attorney-consult">Talk to an Attorney</a>
</div>

</ArticleLayout>
